1.3

Languages

A language is a collection of strings of some fixed alphabet.

Most useful languages are infinite while most alphabets are finite.

Definitions:

  • Alphabet: $\Sigma = \{a, b, c\}$
  • Set of all finite strings: $\Sigma^*$
  • A language is a subset $L\subseteq \Sigma^*$

More Definitions:

  • The string with no symbols is written $\epsilon$. It has length zero.

  • Two strings $s$ and $t$ can be concatenated together: $st$.

  • $s\preceq t$ if there exists a string $u$ such that $su = t$.

Examples

  1. French and English are two distinct languages over the two similar alphabets.

  2. Strings:

    • Bonjour Ã  tous âˆˆ French, so itâ€™s a valid French string.

    • Bonjour Ã  tous $\not\in$ English, so itâ€™s a valid English string.

2

Finite Representations of Languages

2.1

Why finiteness is important

  • Learning

    Representing finite information about an infinite language is the only way that one can learn that language.

2.2

Kleene Algebra

What is an algebra?

An algebra consists of:

  • A set of objects.

    This set of objects can be infinite.

  • A set of operations:

    The operations are just functions that constructs a new object from some input objects.

Kleene algebra:

Objects are languages of an alphabet $\Sigma$.

Operators build new languages.

Basic Kleene operators

  • Constants:
    • $\emptyset$ is the empty language with no strings.
    • $\{\epsilon\}$ is the language that contains only the empty string.
    • $\{a\}$ is the language containing the single-symbol string $a\in\Sigma$.

  • Union:

    $L_1\cup L_2$ is the union of two languages.

  • Concatenation:

    $L_1\cdot L_2$ is the pair-wise concatenation of strings in the two languages: $$L_1\cdot L_2 = \{st: s\in L_1, t\in L_2\}$$

Advanced Kleene operators

  • Powers of languages:

    • $L^0 = \{\epsilon\}$
    • $L^{i+1} = L^i\cdot L$

  • Kleene Closure

    • $L^* = \bigcup_0^\infty L^n$

      So $L^*$ is the all finite contenations of strings in $L$.

Does $\Sigma^*$ make more sense now?

Definition:

Given an alphabet $\Sigma$, languages that can be defined using Kleene algebra are called regular.

2.3

Regular Expressions

Regular expressions are syntactic expressions that represent operations in Kleene algebra.

Given a regular expression, $e$, it defines a language $L(e)$.

The definition of valid regular expressions is quite recursive.

  • a, b, c, â€¦

    Single symbols represent constant languages. $L(a) = \{a\}$

  • $e_1 | e_2$

    $L(e_1 | e_2) = L(e_1) \cup L(e_2)$

  • $e_1 e_2$

    $L(e_1 e_2) = L(e_1) \cdot L(e_2)$

  • $e*$

    $L(e*) = L(e)^*$

  • The empty string represents $\{\epsilon\}$.

Theorem:

In terms of expressive power,
Kleene algebra = Regular Expression
